
[1]scapulary

   SCAP'ULARY, n. A part of the habit of certain religious orders in the
   Romish church, consisting of two narrow slips of cloth worn over the
   gown, covering the back and breast, and extending to the feet. This is
   worn as a badge of peculiar veneration for the virgin Mary.
